{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ec4e4a25-6cd1-4c25-a6f8-b72ad925221e","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` ties the lifetime to an **HTTP request** — each request gets a fresh instance. In MAUI, there's no equivalent request boundary. The app has a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton` — your DbContext lives for the entire app lifetime.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — new instance every time it's injected.\n2. **Create scopes manually** via `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n3. **Dispose explicitly** — call `db.ChangeTracker.Clear()` or dispose/recreate the context when navigating.\n\n`AddTransient` is the simplest fix if your pages don't share a context intentionally.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b304fc36-8356-460c-bb51-386e55d50e9f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common issue when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no equivalent of an HTTP request to define scope boundaries. By default, MAUI apps have a single scope for the entire application lifetime, making `AddScoped` behave essentially like `AddSingleton`.","outputTokens":370,"requestId":"502E:E9FEE:1C79198:1F9B0E1:69FA923A"},"id":"d9bb053e-56e8-4a11-9841-29b0c420714c","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:58:46.186Z","parentId":"9413136d-70f6-4393-b97e-626a02a75924"}
